\chapter{Using mentipy Live}

The API reference below explains the building blocks, but a new user first
needs a map of actual use.  In this chapter, the object of learning is how to
use [[mentipy]] in lecture material: choose a question kind, choose an
authoring path, choose a layout and environment, choose how the respondent URL
is resolved, and then serve the resulting poll.

Both authoring paths generate the same kind of LaTeX fragments.  A PythonTeX
call through [[mentipy.latex]] returns LaTeX during the document build, while
[[mentipy render]] prints the corresponding LaTeX to standard output so it can
be inspected or redirected.  The examples below keep the question text and
rendering options fixed while varying one practical aspect at a time.

These examples keep their state in a local [[./mentipy.json]] store and write
QR artifacts in [[mentipy-obj/]].  That keeps the generated files next to the
manual.

\begin{description}
\item[Build the manual] Run [[make]] in [[doc/]].
\item[Start the server] Run [[mentipy serve --store ./mentipy.json]] in
  [[doc/]].
\item[Answer the polls] Open the generated PDF and scan the QR codes in this
  chapter.
\end{description}

The same progression is also available as interactive command-line lessons.
Run [[mentipy tutorial list]] to see them, take the built-in
[[using-tutorials]] lesson first with
[[mentipy tutorial run using-tutorials]], and then continue with the
mentipy-specific lessons in the listed order.

\ltnote{%
  \textbf{Object of learning}: How to use [[mentipy]] in a real lecture
  workflow.

  \textbf{Critical aspects}: Which question kind to choose, whether to author
  through PythonTeX or the CLI, how the Python and CLI names correspond, how
  layout and [[environment]] affect the emitted LaTeX, how the respondent URL
  is resolved, and why [[mentipy serve]] can require a recompilation.
}

\setpythontexautoprint{false}
\begin{pycode}
from typer.testing import CliRunner
import pydoc

from mentipy.cli import cli
import mentipy.latex

runner = CliRunner()


def render_cli(args):
    result = runner.invoke(cli, args)
    if result.exit_code != 0:
        raise RuntimeError(
            "mentipy "
            + " ".join(args)
            + "\n\n"
            + (result.stdout or "")
            + ("\n" + repr(result.exception) if result.exception else "")
        )
    return result.stdout.rstrip()


def render_help_excerpt():
    output = render_cli(["render", "--help"])
    lines = ["Commands:"]
    for line in output.splitlines():
        if line.startswith("  mc"):
            lines.append(line)
        if line.startswith("  open"):
            lines.append(line)
        if line.startswith("  scale"):
            lines.append(line)
        if line.startswith("  word-cloud"):
            lines.append(line)
    return "\n".join(lines)


def latex_pydoc_excerpt():
    output = pydoc.render_doc(mentipy.latex, renderer=pydoc.plaintext)
    lines = ["FUNCTIONS"]
    for line in output.splitlines():
        stripped = line.lstrip()
        if stripped.startswith("mc("):
            lines.append(line)
        if stripped.startswith("open_text("):
            lines.append(line)
        if stripped.startswith("scale("):
            lines.append(line)
        if stripped.startswith("word_cloud("):
            lines.append(line)
    return "\n".join(lines)
\end{pycode}

\section{Choosing an Authoring Path}

\subsection{A Single-Choice Poll}

This first example uses the common one-answer multiple-choice format.  In a
PythonTeX workflow, the lecture source calls [[mc()]] directly.

\begin{pyblock}
from mentipy.latex import mc

print(
    mc(
        "How confident do you feel about the course goals?",
        ["Very confident", "Somewhat confident", "Not yet"],
        base_url="http://localhost:8080",
        qr_dir="mentipy-obj",
        layout="article+qr",
    )
)
\end{pyblock}

Rendered in the document, that call becomes:
\begin{center}\printpythontex\end{center}

The same question can be rendered without PythonTeX when the lecturer wants the
LaTeX on standard output:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy render mc "How confident do you feel about the course goals?" \
  "Very confident" "Somewhat confident" "Not yet" \
  --base-url http://localhost:8080 --qr-dir mentipy-obj --layout article+qr
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(
    render_cli(
        [
            "render",
            "mc",
            "How confident do you feel about the course goals?",
            "Very confident",
            "Somewhat confident",
            "Not yet",
            "--base-url",
            "http://localhost:8080",
            "--qr-dir",
            "mentipy-obj",
            "--layout",
            "article+qr",
        ]
    )
)
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{cli-mc}

The command prints the following LaTeX:
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{cli-mc}

Included in the document, that output compiles to:
\begin{center}\useprintpythontex{cli-mc}\end{center}

\ltnote{%
  \textbf{Variation pattern}: Contrast

  \textbf{What varies}: The authoring path, PythonTeX versus the CLI.

  \textbf{What stays invariant}: The question kind, the question text, the
  options, the base URL, the QR directory, the layout, and the public name
  [[mc]].

  \textbf{What this reveals}: Both interfaces reach the same rendering
  surface.  PythonTeX embeds the returned LaTeX directly, while the CLI prints
  the same kind of fragment for inspection or redirection.
}

\subsection{A Scale Poll}

The same naming pattern holds for a scale question.  PythonTeX again calls the
helper directly.

\begin{pyblock}
from mentipy.latex import scale

print(
    scale(
        "How fast is today's pace?",
        low=1,
        high=5,
        low_label="Too slow",
        high_label="Too fast",
        base_url="http://localhost:8080",
        qr_dir="mentipy-obj",
        layout="article+qr",
    )
)
\end{pyblock}

Rendered in the document, that call becomes:
\begin{center}\printpythontex\end{center}

The matching CLI command keeps the same public name:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy render scale "How fast is today's pace?" --low 1 --high 5 \
  --low-label "Too slow" --high-label "Too fast" \
  --base-url http://localhost:8080 --qr-dir mentipy-obj --layout article+qr
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(
    render_cli(
        [
            "render",
            "scale",
            "How fast is today's pace?",
            "--low",
            "1",
            "--high",
            "5",
            "--low-label",
            "Too slow",
            "--high-label",
            "Too fast",
            "--base-url",
            "http://localhost:8080",
            "--qr-dir",
            "mentipy-obj",
            "--layout",
            "article+qr",
        ]
    )
)
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{cli-scale}

The command prints the following LaTeX:
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{cli-scale}

Included in the document, that output compiles to:
\begin{center}\useprintpythontex{cli-scale}\end{center}

\ltnote{%
  \textbf{Variation pattern}: Generalization

  \textbf{What stays invariant}: The correspondence between the Python and CLI
  names, here [[scale]] on both sides.

  \textbf{What varies}: The concrete question kind and its scale-specific
