}

\subsection{An Open-Text Poll}

Free-text answers make it easy to collect unexpected questions or requests
while the lecture is in progress.

\begin{pyblock}
from mentipy.latex import open_text

print(
    open_text(
        "What is still unclear?",
        max_chars=160,
        base_url="http://localhost:8080",
        qr_dir="mentipy-obj",
        layout="article+qr",
    )
)
\end{pyblock}

Rendered in the document, that call becomes:
\begin{center}\printpythontex\end{center}

The CLI keeps the same question kind, but its public name is shorter:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy render open "What is still unclear?" --max-chars 160 \
  --base-url http://localhost:8080 --qr-dir mentipy-obj --layout article+qr
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(
    render_cli(
        [
            "render",
            "open",
            "What is still unclear?",
            "--max-chars",
            "160",
            "--base-url",
            "http://localhost:8080",
            "--qr-dir",
            "mentipy-obj",
            "--layout",
            "article+qr",
        ]
    )
)
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{cli-open}

The command prints the following LaTeX:
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{cli-open}

Included in the document, that output compiles to:
\begin{center}\useprintpythontex{cli-open}\end{center}

\ltnote{%
  \textbf{Variation pattern}: Contrast

  \textbf{What varies}: The public name, [[open_text]] in Python versus
  [[open]] in the CLI.

  \textbf{What stays invariant}: The open-text question kind, the prompt, the
  [[max_chars]] limit, the base URL, the QR directory, and the layout.

  \textbf{What this reveals}: The critical correspondence is conceptual rather
  than purely lexical.  The two interfaces still expose the same rendering
  choice even when the names differ.
}

\subsection{An Open-Text Poll for a Code Snippet}

A coding-oriented prompt benefits from the upload form: a respondent can
attach the file they wrote instead of pasting it into a textarea on a phone.
Here the local server will later sit behind an SSH reverse tunnel, so the
rendered QR code should already point at
\url{http://faculty-shell.sys.kth.se:8080} instead of at [[localhost]].
Passing [[fence="python"]] tells [[mentipy]] to wrap uploaded file bodies in a
Python-tagged Markdown fence, so the results page renders the upload as a
language-tagged code block.

\begin{pyblock}
from mentipy.latex import open_text

print(
    open_text(
        "Write a hello-world program in Python and show the command that "
        "runs it.",
        max_chars=2000,
        fence="python",
        base_url="http://faculty-shell.sys.kth.se:8080",
        qr_dir="mentipy-obj",
        layout="article+qr",
    )
)
\end{pyblock}

Rendered in the document, that call becomes:
\begin{center}\printpythontex\end{center}

The CLI keeps the same shape and adds [[--fence]] to match the helper:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy render open \
  "Write a hello-world program in Python and show the command that runs it." \
  --max-chars 2000 --fence python \
  --base-url http://faculty-shell.sys.kth.se:8080 \
  --qr-dir mentipy-obj --layout article+qr
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(
    render_cli(
        [
            "render",
            "open",
            "Write a hello-world program in Python and show the command "
            "that runs it.",
            "--max-chars",
            "2000",
            "--fence",
            "python",
            "--base-url",
            "http://faculty-shell.sys.kth.se:8080",
            "--qr-dir",
            "mentipy-obj",
            "--layout",
            "article+qr",
        ]
    )
)
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{cli-open-fence}

The command prints the following LaTeX:
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{cli-open-fence}

Included in the document, that output compiles to:
\begin{center}\useprintpythontex{cli-open-fence}\end{center}

At serve time, the matching tunnel setup is:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy config mentipy.ssh_tunnel --set dbosk@faculty-shell.sys.kth.se:8080
mentipy serve --public ssh
\end{minted}

The render step only needs the public URL that the QR code should embed.
The runtime tunnel still depends on the SSH server exposing that forwarded
port to the outside world: OpenSSH commonly needs [[GatewayPorts yes]], and
the host firewall must allow inbound TCP on the chosen remote port.  If either
side is missing, [[mentipy serve --public ssh]] now stops with a diagnostic
instead of printing a dead URL.

\ltnote{%
  \textbf{Variation pattern}: Generalization

  \textbf{What varies}: That the open-text helper now also carries a fence
  language hint ([[fence="python"]] on the Python side, [[--fence python]] on
  the CLI).

  \textbf{What stays invariant}: The Python-vs-CLI public-name
  correspondence between [[open_text]] and [[open]], the question prompt, the
  base URL, the QR directory, and the layout.

  \textbf{What this reveals}: The optional fence argument slots into the same
  authoring-path correspondence already established for [[max_chars]] /
  [[--max-chars]].  When a respondent uploads a file, [[mentipy]] wraps the
  body in a fenced Markdown block tagged with the fence language, so the
  results page renders the upload as a language-tagged code block rather than
  as raw prose.
}

\subsection{A Word-Cloud Poll}

A word-cloud poll takes the same free-text input as an open-text poll, but
the results page aggregates the answers into a word cloud rather than
listing them verbatim.  The lecturer chooses the visualisation up front
by passing [[render="svg"]] (the default; it prefers the optional
[[wordcloud]] package when installed and otherwise falls back to
Mentipy's built-in SVG layout, used here), [[render="scaled"]] (a
CSS-sized inline list of words), or
[[render="table"]] (a frequency table).

\begin{pyblock}
from mentipy.latex import word_cloud

print(
    word_cloud(
        "One word that describes this lecture?",
        max_chars=60,
        base_url="http://localhost:8080",
        qr_dir="mentipy-obj",
        layout="article+qr",
    )
)
\end{pyblock}

Rendered in the document, that call becomes:
\begin{center}\printpythontex\end{center}

The CLI mirrors the helper, with one shell flag per visualisation knob.
The kebab-cased subcommand keeps the option grammar readable on a long
line:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy render word-cloud "One word that describes this lecture?" \
  --max-chars 60 \
  --base-url http://localhost:8080 --qr-dir mentipy-obj --layout article+qr
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(
    render_cli(
        [
            "render",
            "word-cloud",
            "One word that describes this lecture?",
            "--max-chars",
            "60",
            "--base-url",
            "http://localhost:8080",
            "--qr-dir",
            "mentipy-obj",
            "--layout",
            "article+qr",
        ]
    )
)
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{cli-wordcloud}

The command prints the following LaTeX:
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{cli-wordcloud}

Included in the document, that output compiles to:
\begin{center}\useprintpythontex{cli-wordcloud}\end{center}

The presentation knobs ([[render]], [[split_words]],
[[min_word_length]], [[extra_stop_words]], [[use_default_stopwords]])
deliberately stay out of the canonical hash.  Editing the slide source
to switch from one visualisation to another and recompiling therefore
keeps the same QR code and the same answer pool: the question's
identity is the prompt and the character limit, not how the resulting
cloud is drawn.

\ltnote{%
  \textbf{Variation pattern}: Generalization

  \textbf{What varies}: The question kind, now a word cloud.  Its
  presentation knobs ([[render]], [[split_words]], [[min_word_length]],
  [[extra_stop_words]], [[use_default_stopwords]]) extend the shared
  authoring surface without touching identity.

  \textbf{What stays invariant}: The PythonTeX-to-CLI parallel between
  [[word_cloud]] and [[word-cloud]], the prompt, the base URL, the QR
  directory, and the layout.  The canonical hash also stays invariant
  when only the visualisation changes: a re-render with a different
  [[render]] mode keeps the same QR and the same answer pool.

  \textbf{What this reveals}: The same authoring-path correspondence
  established for [[mc]], [[scale]], and [[open_text]] generalises to a
  question kind whose visualisation is a first-class authoring choice
  rather than a fixed output shape.
}

\subsection{Discovering the Public Names}

The names are easy to discover from the interfaces themselves.  On the CLI
side, [[mentipy render --help]] lists the available render subcommands:

\begin{minted}{text}
mentipy render --help
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(render_help_excerpt())
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{render-help}
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{render-help}

On the Python side, [[python -m pydoc mentipy.latex]] lists the render helpers
exported from the LaTeX module:

\begin{minted}{text}
python -m pydoc mentipy.latex
\end{minted}

\begin{pycode}
print(latex_pydoc_excerpt())
\end{pycode}
\saveprintpythontex{latex-pydoc}
\useprintpythontex[verbatim]{latex-pydoc}

The runtime command [[mentipy serve]] belongs to the serving step rather than
the render step, so it appears later in this chapter.

